# hilavitkutin-providers backlog

Designed-but-deferred surfaces. Names stay unbacktickled so the
design-doc-source-mismatch lint ignores them. Promoted into
DESIGN.md when shipped.

## M-parameterised arena variant (v1)

A MemoryArena variant parameterised over `M: HasMemoryProvider`
that pulls slab bytes from the consumer's runtime memory provider
at scheduler construction. v0 uses inline `[u8; CAP]` storage at
the type level; v1 covers the case where slab capacity is a
runtime decision (large arenas measured in megabytes that don't
fit a const-generic literal).

Gated on: a real consumer needs runtime slab allocation. Viola's
first integration may surface this if its workload's interner
volume exceeds reasonable inline caps.

## Sync arena variant (v1)

A SyncArena variant using either spinlocks (no_std safe) or
atomics for the cursor and entry table. Today MemoryArena uses
`Cell` + `UnsafeCell` for interior mutability and is `!Sync` as
a result.

Gated on: hilavitkutin's multi-thread scheduling path actually
exercises shared interner access from multiple worker threads. The
single-thread path through morsel dispatch may not need it.

## Future provider modules

ColumnStorage default, Clock default, MemoryProvider default for
libc/Unix targets. Each lands in its own round when consumer
demand surfaces. Per task #253 v0 scope: interner-only.

## Round 202605101036 follow-ups

### Example app skeletons

Topic 11 axis B user-attention. Three example apps autonomous-picked
this round (subject to user swap): `examples/word_count.rs` (canonical
map-reduce with intern + accumulator), `examples/particle_step.rs`
(N-body integrator demonstrating head+tail convergence + arvo
fixed-point math), `examples/audio_mix.rs` (real-time audio mixer
offline-render variant demonstrating predictive parking).

Each example doubles as an integration test: CI runs `cargo run
--example <name>` with assertions on output shape + timing budgets.
The example bodies land in follow-up rounds dedicated to each app;
this BACKLOG entry tracks the v1 commitment.
